description: From Late Middle English dorsal/dorsale, borrowing from Medieval Latin dorsālis (“of or relating to the back”), from dorsum (“the back”) +‎ -ālis (“-al”, adjectival suffix); equivalent to dorsum +‎ -al.

adjectives.description: dorsal (comparative more dorsal, superlative most dorsal)

definitionGroups.group: (anatomy, zootomy) With respect to, or concerning the side in which the backbone is located, or the analogous side of an invertebrate.

entries.meaning: (anatomy) Relating to the top surface of the foot or hand.
(linguistics, of a sound) Produced using the dorsum of the tongue.
examples: Coordinate terms: coronal, labial, laryngeal, radical

entries.meaning: (of a knife) Having only one sharp side.
(botany) Relating to the surface naturally inferior, as of a leaf.
(botany) Relating to the surface naturally superior, as of a creeping hepatic moss.
(art) A hanging, usually of rich stuff, at the back of a throne, altar, etc.
(zootomy, in snakes) Any of the longitudinal series of plates that encircle the body, excluding the ventral scales.
(linguistics) A sound produced using the dorsum of the tongue.
